glossdef.programlisting:
/*
 * HELLO WORLD program
 * by Jack Applin and Robert Heckendorn, 1985
 * (Note: depends on being able to modify elements of argv[],
 * which is not guaranteed by ANSI and often not possible.)
 */
main(v,c)char**c;{for(v[c++]="Hello, world!\n)";
(!!c)[*c]&&(v--||--c&&execlp(*c,*c,c[!!c]+!!c,!c));
**c=!c)write(!!*c,*c,!!**c);}

glossdef.para:
Note that the formal SI metric prefix for 1000 is ‘k’;
   some use this strictly, reserving ‘K’ for multiplication by
   1024 (KB is thus ‘kilobytes’).

[Unix] Commonwealth Hackish variant of RTFM;
  expands to ‘Read The Bloody Manual’.  RTBM is often the entire
  text of the first reply to a question from a newbie;
  the second would escalate to
  RTFM.

This version of the jargon lexicon has been described (with
   altogether too much truth for comfort) as an example of second-system
   effect run amok on jargon-1&endellipsis;

Metaphorically, Get stuffed. From the title of a
  famous parody that can easily be found with a web search on this phrase;
  figure 1, in fact, depicts the digitus impudicus.

A Unix symbolic link, particularly when it confuses you, points to
  nothing at all, or results in your ending up in some completely unexpected
  part of the filesystem&endellipsis;

The number of years it takes to finish one's thesis.  Occurs in
  stories in the following form: He started on his thesis; 2 pi years
  later&ellipsis;

To experience serendipity.  I went shopping and won big;
  there was a 2-for-1 sale. See 
